      "solution": "def f(u, m, n, b, km, kn)\n  v = b * u - b ** kn\n  [u / b ** (kn - km) - m + 1, 0].max - [u - n, 0].max +\n  (km...kn).inject(0) { |s, _| s + (v /= b) + 1 }\nend\n  \ndef solve(m, n, b, x)\n  km, kn = [m, n].map { |j| j.to_s(b).size }\n  u = (b ** (kn - 1)...b ** kn).bsearch { |u| f(u, m, n, b, km, kn) >= x }\n  u / b ** (f(u, m, n, b, km, kn) - x + (u > n ? 1 : 0))\nend\n\nm, n, b, x = gets.split.map(&:to_i)\n\nputs solve(m, n, b, x)\n\n=begin\nPython solution\n\nm,n,b,x=map(int,input().split())\ndef C(p,lim):\n    s,q=0,p+1\n    while p<=lim:\n        s+=min(lim+1,q)-p \n        p,q=p*b,q*b\n    return s\nv=1\nwhile True:\n    gap=C(v,n)-C(v,m-1)\n    if x>gap:\n        x-=gap; v+=1\n    else:\n        if v>=m:\n            x-=1\n            if x==0: print(v); break\n        v*=b\n=end\n",
      "statement": "Given four integers [[m]], [[n]], [[b]], and [[x]]:\n  -  Consider all integers from [[m]] to [[n]] <<(inclusive)>>.\n  -   Sort these integers as if they were written in base-[[b]], in <<lexicographical>> order.\n\nFind the [[x]]-th integer in this order and return it in <<base-10>>.\n\n<<Example:>>\n<<INPUT:>> 2 15 3 8\n\nLet's first translate the numbers from <<2 to 15>> into <<base 3>>:\n2 => 2\n3 => 10\n4 => 11\n5 => 12\n6 => 20\n7 => 21\n8 => 22\n9 => 100\n10 => 101\n11 => 102\n12 => 110\n13 => 111\n14 => 112\n15 => 120\n\nLet's then sort them <<lexicographically>>:\n[10, 100, 101, 102, 11, 110, 111,  112, 12, 120,  2, 20, 21, 22]\n\nThe <<8th number>> (starting from 1) is 112, i.e. 14 in our decimal system.\n<<OUTPUT:>> 14",
